      "rationale": "Standard NAFEMS benchmark suite (LE1, LE10, NL1) and Ansys internal verification cases executed prior to production runs. All results within 1% of closed-form analytical solutions, satisfying Gradation 2 requirements for code verification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study with GCI < 5% on all QoIs; Richardson extrapolation applied to stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study conducted (coarse 1.5 mm, medium 0.8 mm, fine 0.4 mm global element size at screw-rod interface). Grid Convergence Index (GCI) < 3.2% for all three QoIs on the fine mesh. Richardson extrapolation confirms discretization error is within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson residual convergence criterion < 1e-4 enforced; energy convergence < 1e-3 for nonlinear steps.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analysis used Newton-Raphson iteration with force residual tolerance 1e-4 and energy criterion 1e-3. Convergence achieved within 12 substeps for all load cases. No divergence or spurious oscillation observed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup by second analyst; checklist-based review against ASTM F1717 boundary condition specifications.",
      "rationale": "A second qualified analyst independently reviewed all boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and contact definitions against the ASTM F1717 standard and the internal modeling protocol. No discrepancies identified. Checklist archived in the design history file."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastoplastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening validated for Ti-6Al-4V; contact formulation captures screw-rod interface nonlinearity.",
      "rationale": "The model employs a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model for Ti-6Al-4V (E=114 GPa, σ_y=880 MPa, tangent modulus=1.2 GPa) consistent with literature and coupon test data. Augmented Lagrange contact with frictional coefficient μ=0.2 captures the screw-rod bearing interface. Model form is appropriate for the compression-bending regime of ASTM F1717."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon testing and ASTM B265 certificate of conformance; geometric inputs from calibrated CMM measurements.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, ultimate tensile strength) derived from lot-specific dogbone coupon tests (N=6 per lot) and confirmed against ASTM B265 CoC. Screw and rod geometry inputs from CMM measurements with ±0.01 mm uncertainty. Uncertainty in inputs propagated via Monte Carlo sampling (N=1000) to confirm QoI sensitivity is within bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from two independent laboratories; samples from commercial production lots.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from commercial production lots tested across two independent laboratories (FDA OSEL and DePuy Synthes). Sample selection follows ASTM F1717 requirements. Inter-laboratory variability characterized; coefficient of variation < 6% for stiffness QoI."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span clinically relevant load magnitudes and rates; minimum two distinct test configurations required.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single ASTM F1717 standard configuration (5 mm/min crosshead displacement, ambient temperature, standard block geometry). While this configuration is well-characterized and reproducible, only one test condition was evaluated. This falls short of the required level 3, which demands at least two distinct configurations to assess condition sensitivity. This is a documented limitation acknowledged in the credibility assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions, geometry, and material inputs demonstrably equivalent to physical test setup; traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Full traceability matrix prepared mapping each FEA input parameter to its physical test counterpart. Block geometry, loading fixture dimensions, screw insertion torque (converted to preload), and material certificates all documented. CMM measurements of test fixtures used to set FEA geometric boundary conditions. Traceability confirmed by independent reviewer."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10% for all three QoIs across all 11 constructs.",
      "rationale": "Validation metric E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Section 8 using combined simulation and experimental uncertainties. Results: stiffness E/uval=1.41, yield force E/uval=1.62, force at 40 mm E/uval=1.78 — all below 1.96 threshold. Maximum percent difference 9.8%. Acceptance criteria met for all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements for pedicle screw constructs.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly relevant to the clinical failure modes of pedicle screw constructs (fatigue fracture, permanent deformation). These QoIs are also the metrics cited in FDA guidance for 510(k) submissions for spinal fixation systems, confirming their regulatory relevance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities directly reproduce the COU geometry, loading mode, and material system; no extrapolation beyond validated domain for the COU prediction.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw geometry, Ti-6Al-4V material system, and ASTM F1717 compression-bending loading mode as the COU. No geometric scaling, material substitution, or loading mode extrapolation is required. The validation domain fully encompasses the COU prediction domain."
    }
